caption.p:
Images of pycnidia (indicated by arrows) and pycnidiospores from wheat leaves infected with 4 × 106 spores/ml from IPO323 and ΔztabaA, ΔztbrlA1, ΔztbrlA2, ΔztflbB, and ΔztflbC mutants. (A,G) IPO323; (B,H) ΔztabaA;
(C,I) Δztbrla1;
(D,J) ΔztbrlA2;
(E,K) ΔztflbB;
(F,L) ΔztflbC at 28 days post-infection (d.p.i.). The knock-out mutant strains were all able to produce pycnidia and pycnidiospores, and these were morphologically similar to the IPO323 strain. The ΔztbrlA2 mutant produced fewer pycnidia, and these took longer to develop compared to the IPO323 strain. Fewer spores were harvested from the ΔztbrlA2 and ΔztflbC mutants.
